IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - xinetd configuration files modified
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the files inside "/etc/xinetd.d/" directory, which contains the configuration files for each service managed by xinetd. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - sudo files modified (ATT&CK T1548.003)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors sudo files. Adversaries may use these files to perform sudo caching and/or use the suoders file to elevate privileges. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - System driver files modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in file attributes Created, LastModified, Permissions, Owner, Group, Size and Contents of .sys files under %WINDIR%\system32\drivers path.
Also the rule provides configuration option to ignore files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - csh/tcsh configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1059.004, T1546.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may abuse Unix shells to execute various commands or payloads or establish persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Default Debugger changed
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when registry data values for Windows default debugger have changed. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - 'ActiveX Compatibility' registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1112)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when there is any change in the 'ActiveX Compatibility' registry key set. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - SAM registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1098, T1136)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when there is a change in registry key entries where SAM Domain Account User's details found. When a user is added to the local system, new registry keys are added under the SAM Domain Account registry path. Generally, these registry entries contain user details like login name, user number, sid name, machine name etc. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /bin directory modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in file attributes in any file under /bin path. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /etc directory modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in attributes of any file under /etc directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Boot files modified (ATT&CK T1542)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors boot process related files in the "/lib" directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /lib directory modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in attributes of any file under /lib directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /sbin directory modified

This rule alerts when there is a change in file attributes in any file under /sbin path. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Default firewall rules modified (ATT&CK T1562.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors files inside the "/lib/firwalld" directory which holds default firewall rules like default zones and common services. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - modeprobe configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1547.006)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the configuration files of the modeprobe utility. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Registry values of event log modified (ATT&CK T1070.001, T1562.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when attributes of registry subkeys and data values changed for settings of Windows Event Viewer. For additional information, see the Details tab.
The rule also provides configuration options to choose registry key and value attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - SSL configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1587.003)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the openssl configuration and SSL certificates inside the "/lib/ssl" directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Static boot loader files modified (ATT&CK T1542)
IntegrityRule.Description: The "/boot" directory contains the files needed to boot the system. Adversaries may abuse Pre-OS Boot mechanisms as a way to establish persistence on a system. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Microsoft hotfixes registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1112)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when attributes of registry subkeys changed where Windows Hotfix updates found. It monitors all registry keys where Hotfix entries gets updated in Windows Registry. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to choose registry key attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - User access control files modified (ATT&CK T1068)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the change in files inside the "/lib/security" directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Network configuration files modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in file attributes of Network configuration files found under %WINDIR%\inf (e.g., C:\WINDOWS\inf) directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to exclude files from monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Directory attributes of /bin modified (ATT&CK T1222.002)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Disk configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1561.002)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Shared object files modified

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Directory attributes of /sbin modified (ATT&CK T1222.002)

Note: The rule also provides configuration options to select directory attributes to monitor.

Note: Configuration options are provided to exclude certain files and directories.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Component Object Model Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1546.015)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can use this system to insert malicious code that can be executed in place of legitimate software through hijacking the COM references and relationships as a means for persistence. Hijacking a COM object requires a change in the Windows Registry to replace a reference to a legitimate system component which may cause that component to not work when executed. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - System .dll or .exe files modified (ATT&CK T1036.003, T1222.001)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in .dll or .exe files under %WINDIR%\system32 path. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: This rule provides configuration option to ignore files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Boot or Logon Autostart Execution: Port Monitors (ATT&CK T1547.010)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors a registry key that the print spooler users to monitor printer ports. Adversaries can use this technique to load malicious code at startup that will persist on system reboot and execute as SYSTEM. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Application shimming detected (ATT&CK T1546.011)
IntegrityRule.Description:
The Microsoft Windows Application Compatibility Infrastructure/Framework (Application Shim) was created to allow for backward compatibility of software as the operating system codebase changes over time.
However, certain shims can be abused. Utilizing these shims may allow an adversary to perform several malicious acts such as elevate privileges, install backdoors, disable defenses like Windows Defender, etc. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Task scheduler entries modified (ATT&CK T1053.005)
IntegrityRule.Description: An adversary may use job scheduling to execute programs at system startup or on a scheduled basis for persistence, to conduct execution as part of lateral movement, to gain root privileges, or to run a process under the context of a specific account. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - AppCert DLL Registry values modified (ATT&CK T1546.009)
IntegrityRule.Description: Dynamic-link libraries (DLLs) that are specified in the AppCertDLLs value in the Registry key HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager are loaded into every process that calls various ubiquitously used application programming interface (API) functions. This value can be abused to obtain persistence and privilege escalation by causing a malicious DLL to be loaded and run in the context of separate processes on the computer. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Security support providers (SSP) registry key modified (ATT&CK T1547.005)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may abuse security support providers (SSPs) to execute DLLs. These SSP DLLs are loaded into the Local Security Authority (LSA) process at system start. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - bash command history cleared (ATT&CK T1059.004)
IntegrityRule.Description:
Adversaries can use a variety of methods to clear command history, clearing their tracks. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: By default this rule only monitors root command history. Additional users to monitor can be added under Configuration Options in the Configuration tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Accessibility features registry keys or files modified (ATT&CK T1546.008, T1546.012)
IntegrityRule.Description:
An adversary can modify the way these programs are launched to get a command prompt or backdoor without logging into the system. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: This rule provides configuration option to select files for monitoring.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Time Provider Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1547.003)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may abuse this architecture to establish persistence, specifically by registering and enabling a malicious DLL as a time provider. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Service Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1574.011)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can change the service binPath/ImagePath to point to a different executable under their control. When the service starts or is restarted, then the adversary-controlled program will execute, allowing the adversary to gain persistence and/or privilege escalation to the account context the service is set to execute under (local/domain account, SYSTEM, LocalService, or NetworkService). For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Removable Device Detected (ATT&CK T1092)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can perform command and control between compromised hosts on potentially disconnected networks using removable media to transfer commands from system to system. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Root Certificate Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1553.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: Installation of a root certificate on a compromised system would give an adversary a way to degrade the security of that system. Adversaries have used this technique to avoid security warnings prompting users when compromised systems connect over HTTPS to adversary controlled web servers that spoof legitimate websites in order to collect login credentials. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - NetSh Helper DLL Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1546.007)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can use netsh.exe with helper DLLs to proxy execution of arbitrary code in a persistent manner when netsh.exe is executed automatically with another persistence technique or if other persistent software is present on the system. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - USB storage device detected (ATT&CK T1052.001, T1092)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when a USB storage device is plugged in the system. It monitors the changes in registry key to detect the attachment and removal of USB storage device. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - AppInit DLL Registry values modified (ATT&CK T1546.010)
IntegrityRule.Description: The monitored registry values can be used and abused by adversaries to obtain persistence and privilege escalation by causing a malicious DLL to be loaded and run in the context of separate processes on the computer. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Attributes of log file modified (ATT&CK T1070, T1222.001)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in any file attributes for a given log file on Windows platform. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to add files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes modified (ATT&CK T1070.002, T1222.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
Adversaries may modify permissions on files to gain additional access, hide evidence of an intrusion or to clear their tracks. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to add files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Active Directory
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in directory attributes and file attributes of all files found in %WINDIR%\system32\NTDS and %WINDIR%\system32\SYSVOL directories. It monitors change in registry keys and data values created by Microsoft Active Directory.
The rule also provides configuration options to select file attributes to monitor and to provide file names to ignore monitoring files under %WINDIR%\system32\NTDS and %WINDIR%\system32\SYSVOL directories.

LogInspectionRule.Description: To detect Microsoft LDAP query execution in Windows.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability - 2
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Unvalidated Redirect And Forward Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects Unvalidated redirect and forward in HTTP traffic via request parameters, query string and headers. Unvalidated redirects and forwards are possible when a web application accepts untrusted input that could cause the web application to redirect the request to a URL contained within untrusted input. By modifying unvalidated URL input to a malicious site, an attacker may successfully launch multiple social engineering attacks.
Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted domain/IP in the configuration page. The rule will allow all redirects and forwards unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Access Event Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if Windows Events (Security, Application and System) are accessed by remote machine using 'Psloglist.exe' command line tool through SMBv2 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Access Event Through SMBv1 Protocol Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if Windows Events (Security, Application and System) are accessed by remote machine using 'Psloglist.exe' command line tool through SMBv1 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Block Administrative Share - 1 (ATT&CK T1021.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Administrative Shares are the default network shares created by all Windows NT-based operating systems. These default shares share every hard drive partition in the system and the windows directory. This filter blocks attempt to access administrative share on a windows machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Executable File Download On Network Share Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect executable file being accessed over SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when executable files are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Client Restrict Executable File Downloads
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks EXE file downloads. Administrator can configure this filter and allow certain EXE file downloads.

PayloadFilter2.Name: WinRM Service Detected & Powershell RCE Over HTTP - Client (ATT&CK T1021.006, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services). This filter detects its generic usage as well as through PowerShell.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Attempt To Enumerate Windows User Accounts (ATT&CK T1087)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter identifies an attempt to enumerate user account information on a Windows host. There are valid cases where an administrator may want to enumerate accounts on a remote system but any alert from this filter should be investigated. Note: This rule should not be assigned to domain controllers.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Terminal Services (RDP) Server Traffic - 1 (ATT&CK T1021.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects RDP server traffic based on heuristics. An event indicates suspicious activity since RDP traffic over non-standard ports indicates the presence of a backdoor RDP server installation.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of WMI Execute Methods - Client (ATT&CK T1047)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 1 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 4 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Many SSH Client Key Exchange Requests (ATT&CK T1499.002, T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SSH client key exchange requests from the same source IP. Many client key exchange requests in short span of time are highly suspicious. This DPI rule could be helpful in identifying SSH bruteforce attack.
Note: Configuration options are provided to change the frequency to alert on.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMBLoris Denial Of Service Vulnerability
PayloadFilter2.Description:
SMBLoris is a remote and uncredentialed denial of service attack against Microsoft Windows SMB and Unix/Linux Samba servers using memory exhaustion technique. This DPI rule detects an attempt to exploit servers using SMBLoris.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious TLS Request (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule identifies the malicious TLS request which can be used to compromise a web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious TLS Request - 1 (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule identifies the malicious TLS traffic t which can be used to compromise the web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of Linux Executable File (ATT&CK T1608.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detect the upload of a Linux executable file on a web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potential Malicious Client Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potential Malicious Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Apache Log4j Remote Code Execution Vulnerability (CVE-2021-44228)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects an attempt to inject JNDI requests in HTTP request. While not inherently malicious, the presence of JNDI code in the HTTP URI or Headers can be indicative of an attempt to exploit a known code execution vulnerability in Log4j.
Configuration Note: Administrators are advised to configure this rule with IP(s) of trusted host(s) to allow JNDI request traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: HTTP Web Client Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a smart filter that decodes the Web Client traffic and is used by other web client filters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Downloading Of PowerShell Scripts Through SMB Share (ATT&CK T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: PowerShell may also be used to download and run PowerShell scripts from the Internet, which can be executed from disk or in memory without touching disk. Adversaries may use PowerShell to execute malicious PowerShell scripts that may cause Damage of the system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified DLL Side Loading Attempt Over Network Share (ATT&CK T1574.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
DLL side-loading vulnerability specifically occur when Windows Side-by-Side (WinSxS) manifests are not explicit enough about characteristics of the DLL to be loaded. Attackers may take advantage of a legitimate program that is vulnerable to side-loading to load a malicious DLL. Successful exploitation of this vulnerability could lead to remote code execution. This rule detects attempts to load DLL files which are not signed by Microsoft or Adobe Corporation over network shares.
Note: Triggers of this rule need to be analyzed further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Powershell Remote Command Execution Via WinRM - HTTP (Request) (ATT&CK T1021.006, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services).
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Registry Access Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected (ATT&CK T1012)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if Windows registry is accessed through SMBv2 protocol by the remote user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: WinRM Service Detected & Powershell RCE Over HTTP (ATT&CK T1021.006, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services). This filter detects its generic usage as well as through PowerShell.
Note: In some network environments, this rule can generate many triggers and will need further investigation to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Create Activity Over Network Share (ATT&CK T1486, T1080)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB create operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file create operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file create, write and delete operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule decodes the Cross-Site Scripting attack patterns and helps the dependent rule to take the action.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote System Discovery Over SMB (ATT&CK T1018)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect remote system discovery over SMB. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Domain-Level Account Discovery Over SMB (ATT&CK T1087.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect domain account discovery over SMB. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Zoho ManageEngine ADManager Plus Unrestricted File Upload Vulnerability (CVE-2021-20130)
PayloadFilter2.Description: An unrestricted file upload vulnerability has been reported in ManageEngine ADManager Plus. The vulnerability is due to lack of validation of uploaded files in PasswordExpiryAction class. A remote authenticated attacker can exploit the vulnerability by sending crafted requests to the server. Successful exploitation could result in unrestricted file upload and remote code execution in the security context of SYSTEM.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft SharePoint Server Remote Code Execution Vulnerability (CVE-2021-41344)
PayloadFilter2.Description: An insecure deserialization vulnerability has been reported in SharePoint. The specific flaw exists within the handling of custom workflows. An attacker can leverage this vulnerability to execute code in the context of the web service account.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Google Chrome Use After Free Vulnerability (CVE-2020-15994)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Google Chrome is vulnerable to Use After Free vulnerability which allows a remote attacker to execute arbitrary code.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Google Chrome Type Confusion Vulnerability (CVE-2021-30588)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Google Chrome is vulnerable to type confusion vulnerability which allows a remote attacker to execute arbitrary code.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious User Agent In HTTP Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the suspicious user-agent header of an HTTP request used for scanning and attacking web server or web application.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure additional user agents, remove existing user agents and the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote System Discovery Over LSARPC (ATT&CK T1018)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect remote system discovery over DCERPC bind request for LSARPC pipe . This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Chromium Memory Corruption Vulnerability (CVE-2021-21118)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Chromium is vulnerable to Memory Corruption Vulnerability. An attacker can execute arbitrary code inside a sandbox on a victim machine by using a specially crafted HTML page.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Shellcode Over Network Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. This rule will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Chromium Sandbox Bypass Vulnerability (CVE-2021-21132)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Inappropriate implementation in DevTools in Chromium allowed a remote attacker to potentially perform a sandbox escape via a crafted Chrome Extension.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Multiple SSH Connections Detected (ATT&CK T1499.002, T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SSH server connections in a certain time frame. This can be result of Denial of Service or Brute force attack.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode Encoders For Client
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. To evade detection or due to protocol constraints, shellcode is often encoded using various shellcode encoders. This filter will identify shellcode encoders that are typically used by automated exploitation tools such as Metasploit.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSH Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021.004)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects SSH server traffic based on heuristics.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter and to allow the client IP address to make SSH connection. Rule will trigger for all SSH clients if not configured with allowed IP address.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Data Exfiltration Over DNS (Response) Protocol (T1048)
PayloadFilter2.Description: DNS date exfiltration is a way to exchange data between two computers without any direct connection. The data is exchanged through DNS protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Office File With Embedded Executable File
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is intended to block any Microsoft Office file having OLE compound document with embedded executable file. The detection is for identifying such Microsoft Office files when downloaded over web. Attackers may use crafted Microsoft Office files having embedded executable file to run arbitrary code remotely.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Drovorub Command And Control Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered by this filter when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Fraudulent Digital Certificate
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule heuristically prevents the exchange of Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificate whose trust has been revoked.
Ref: Microsoft Security Advisory (2798897).

PayloadFilter2.Name: Apache Log4j Denial of Service Vulnerability (CVE-2021-45105)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Apache Log4j2 is vulnerable to a denial of service vulnerability. Apache Log4j2 did not protect from uncontrolled recursion from self-referential lookups. This allows an attacker with control over Thread Context Map data to cause a denial of service when a crafted string is interpreted.
Note: Given the nature of this vulnerability, generic detection is not possible. Only limited detection is available.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Port Mapper Decoder Passive FTP Server
PayloadFilter2.Description: FTP servers can run in Active and Passive modes. In passive mode, the FTP server opens a dynamic port, sends the FTP client the server's IP address to connect to and the port on which it is listening over the control stream and waits for a connection from the FTP client. This filter decodes the FTP port mapper traffic to find out the dynamic port number over FTP control connection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Command Injection Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Command injection is an attack technique that allows an attacker to inject and execute commands in the vulnerable application. An attacker can exploit command injection vulnerability with a command sequence appended to the appropriate format or escape string to execute arbitrary commands. Successful exploitation results in a system compromise, disclosure or modification of data. This is a heuristic based rule to block command injection attacks. In some network environment further investigation will be required to confirm the attack.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure the parameter names where commands are allowed.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Internet Explorer VBScript ShellExecute Command
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the use of VBscript with ShellExceute command in html files, which may allow remote attacker to gain unauthorized access and execute arbitrary code.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks. Customers are advised to configure this rule with allowed IP addresses, from which the VBScript ShellExecute command is allowed to run in Microsoft Internet Explorer.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified BADRABBIT Ransomware Download Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule blocks download of malicious JavaScript code and fake flash installer used by BADRABBIT ransomware.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Unsecured Credentials - Cloud Instance Metadata API (ATT&CK T1552.005)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects attempts to access the Cloud Instance Metadata API and collect credentials and other sensitive data. It currently protects workloads on the following Cloud Service Providers: Amazon Web Services, Google Cloud Platform and Microsoft Azure.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. The filter will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) Connection Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to identify Remote Desktop connection request using Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP). In some network environment, many RDP connection requests, could lead to Denial of Service (DOS) condition.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the number of requests and the time interval. After the frequency of RDP connection requests matched as per the configuration, the rule will prevent any further RDP connection from the same Source IP for the configured period of time.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reflected File Download Attack in URI Query Parameter
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Reflected File Download (RFD) is a web attack vector that enables attackers to gain complete control over a user system. In an RFD attack, the user follows a malicious link to a trusted domain resulting in a file download from that domain.
Note: Configuration option is provided to add the executable file extensions to block the RFD attack for the file extensions. Administrators are suggested to add executable file extensions to block the RFD attack according to their Web Application file extension support. The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm their domain are being used to carry out RFD attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Fraudulent Digital Certificate - 1
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically prevents the exchange of Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificate whose trust has been revoked.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows Active Directory Domain Services Elevation of Privilege Vulnerability Over SMB (CVE-2021-42278)
PayloadFilter2.Description: An elevation of privilege vulnerability has been reported in the Active Directory Domain Services of Microsoft Windows. The vulnerability is due to insufficient validation of accounts attributes. A remote, authenticated attacker can exploit this vulnerability by impersonating domain controller accounts. Successful exploitation could result in privilege escalation.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows Active Directory Domain Services Elevation of Privilege Vulnerability Over LDAP (CVE-2021-42278)

Successful exploitation could result in privilege escalation.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Zoho ManageEngine ADManager Plus Unrestricted File Upload Vulnerability (CVE-2021-37539)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Zoho ManageEngine ADManager Plus is prone to unrestricted file upload vulnerability. This can lead to arbitrary code execution in the security context as SYSTEM.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Strapi Framework Remote Code Execution Vulnerability (CVE-2019-19609)
PayloadFilter2.Description: The Strapi framework is vulnerable to a remote code execution vulnerability. Vulnerability exist in the Install and Uninstall Plugin components of the Admin panel, as it does not sanitize the plugin name, due to which attackers can inject arbitrary shell commands and execute them with the help of vulnerable function.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Windows Search Protocol Network Traffic Over SMB
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule intends to identify and block the network traffic for Windows Search Protocol (WSP). This works on SMBv1 and SMBv2.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Unix Samba Server Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and help other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected HTTP Server Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect HTTP Server traffic on a host. By default, any HTTP Sever traffic identified on TCP ports other than the commonly used 80 and 8080 will trigger this filter. Rogue HTTP servers may indicate policy violations or presence of malicious software on the computer.
This filter will only trigger once per 24 hours for a given host to prevent excessive logging. The monitored ports and frequency of event settings can be modified on the Configuration tab should your environment require different configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected HTTP Traffic Over Secured HTTPS Channels
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect unsecured HTTP Server traffic on specified secured channels where encryption should be used for all connections. By default, HTTPS traffic is commonly used on port 443. Rogue HTTP servers may indicate policy violations or presence of malicious software on the computer.
Administrators are recommended to apply this filter to all ports that use HTTPS for encrypted communication.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified SAMBA DCERPC AUTH LEVEL CONNECT Password Validate Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule, which detects if the AUTH LEVEL CONNECT is used as a DCERPC level authentication protection for Password Validate request. AUTH LEVEL CONNECT is not secure, an attacker having MITM situation could tamper the traffic and discover other domain passwords.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SMTP Server Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects SMTP server traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Obfuscated JavaScript For Internet Explorer
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule identifies suspicious Internet Explorer exploits that use obfuscated JavaScript. Attackers tend to obfuscate malicious JavaScript to avoid detection by IPS/IDS product.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Apache APISIX 'uri-block' Plugin Path Traversal Vulnerability (CVE-2021-43557)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Apache APISIX is prone to a path traversal vulnerability. Remote attackers could use this vulnerability to access protected service

PayloadFilter2.Name: Zoho ManageEngine ServiceDesk Plus Authentication Bypass Vulnerability (CVE-2021-37415)
PayloadFilter2.Description: An authentication bypass vulnerability has been reported in Zoho ManageEngine ServiceDesk Plus. The vulnerability is due to an error in normalizing REST API URLs before applying security filtering. A remote attacker could exploit this vulnerability by sending crafted requests to the target server. Successful exploitation could allow the attacker to bypass authentication.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Dolibarr ERP And CRM Stored Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerability (CVE-2021-33618)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A stored cross-site scripting vulnerability has been reported in the Group module of Dolibarr ERP and CRM Suite. The vulnerability is due to insufficient sanitization of user-supplied data during group creation. A remote, authenticated attacker could exploit this vulnerability by sending a crafted message to a vulnerable server. Successful exploitation could result in execution of script code in the security context of target user's browser.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Domain-Level Permission Groups Discovery Over SMB (ATT&CK T1069.002)

This DPI rule is to detect domain permission groups discovery over SMB. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

A remote authenticated attacker can exploit the vulnerability by sending crafted requests to the server. Successful exploitation could result in unrestricted file upload and remote code execution in the security context of SYSTEM.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Dolibarr ERP And CRM Command Injection Vulnerability (CVE-2021-33816)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A command injection vulnerability for the Dolibarr ERP/CRM package has been disclosed. The vulnerability is due to insufficient input validation checks on user provided data in the Website module. A remote, authenticated attacker could exploit this vulnerability by sending a maliciously crafted request to the server. A successful attack may result in arbitrary command injection on the target server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Port Mapper Decoder

A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and helps other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified DCERPC EfsRpcOpenFileRaw Call Over SMB Protocol (PetitPotam)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects an EfsRpcOpenFileRaw request using the encrypting file system remote (EFSRPC) protocol.
The EfsRpcOpenFileRaw method is used to open an encrypted object on the server for backup or restore. While not inherently malicious, known exploits of the PetitPotam vulnerability make use of this request.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Netlogon Elevation Of Privilege Vulnerability (Zerologon) (CVE-2020-1472)
PayloadFilter2.Description: An elevation of privilege vulnerability exists when an attacker establishes a vulnerable Netlogon secure channel connection to a domain controller, using the Netlogon Remote Protocol (MS-NRPC). An attacker who successfully exploited the vulnerability could run a specially crafted application on a device on the network. To exploit the vulnerability, an unauthenticated attacker would be required to use MS-NRPC to connect to a domain controller to obtain domain administrator access.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified NTLM Brute Force Attempt (ZeroLogon) (CVE-2020-1472)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based DPI rule to detect Brute Force attempt using NTLM authentication for ZeroLogon vulnerability.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Malicious Java JAR Files
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks malicious java jar files which are known to have been used in the wild.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Download Of A Suspicious PowerShell Script File Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule detects a malicious PowerShell script file being download.
Note: Trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Samba RPC Netlogon NetrServerPasswordSet Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: The Netlogon server implementation in smbd in Samba performs a free operation on an uninitialized stack pointer, which allows remote attackers to execute arbitrary code. This DPI rule detects the rpc netlogon NetServerPasswordSet request.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Java Exploit
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect java vulnerability being exploited in the wild.

This DPI rule detects an attempt to inject JNDI requests in HTTP request. While not inherently malicious, the presence of JNDI code in the HTTP URI or Headers can be indicative of an attempt to exploit a known code execution vulnerability in Log4j.

To exploit the vulnerability, an unauthenticated attacker would be required to use MS-NRPC to connect to a domain controller to obtain domain administrator access.

Successful attacks may allow a remote attacker to execute arbitrary commands.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Spring Boot Actuator Endpoint Access Attempt
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule detects the attempt to access publicly open spring boot actuator endpoints.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote PWDUMP Through SMBv1 Protocol Detected

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Packed Executable Download Over HTTP

Note: TIFF files can be embedded in Microsoft Office files in multiple ways. This rule detects TIFF files embedded in Microsoft Office in certain known ways. And the rule does not detect Microsoft Office Open XML format (docx, pptx, etc.) files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Graphics Component Remote Code Execution Vulnerability (CVE-2013-3906) - 1
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote code execution vulnerability that exists in the way affected components handle specially crafted TIFF images. An attacker could exploit this vulnerability by convincing a user to open a specially crafted file, or browse specially crafted web content.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Cobalt Strike Default Self-signed SSL/TLS Certificate
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching known Cobalt Strike default self-signed SSL/TLS certificate exchange pattern is observed.
